{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474998","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474998"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:28:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:28:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12481"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12481"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.05,0.06,0.06,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4988"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48709"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4988"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33659"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"5872"},{"type":"tags","id":"9398"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8322"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44130"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48709"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA nine-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his mother for episodes of \u0022spacing out\u0022 over the past few weeks. According to his mother, these episodes occur several times a day at any time, usually lasting for a few seconds. During the episodes, he appears to lose awareness of his surroundings and is unresponsive to verbal or physical cues. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with a pulse rate of 80/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. His cardiovascular examination reveals a soft systolic murmur. The rest of his physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial diagnostic investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["EEG","MRI brain","24-hour Holter monitor","Serum electrolytes","Echocardiogram"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe presentation of this nine-year-old boy is suggestive of absence seizures, a common form of childhood epilepsy. The brief episodes of unresponsiveness occurring multiple times a day, with sudden onset and offset, are characteristic of absence seizures. An \u003Cstrong\u003EEEG\u003C/strong\u003E (electroencephalogram) is the most appropriate initial diagnostic investigation in this case. It can detect the typical 3 Hz spike-and-wave discharges associated with absence seizures, which are often provoked during the EEG by hyperventilation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E24-hour Holter monitor\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if cardiac syncope was suspected. The presence of a soft systolic murmur raises the possibility of a cardiac cause, but the description of the episodes (multiple brief events daily) is more consistent with absence seizures than cardiac syncope. However, if the EEG is normal, cardiac evaluation may be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eechocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be a reasonable investigation given the presence of a murmur. However, given the typical presentation of absence seizures, it\u0027s not the most appropriate initial investigation. If the EEG is normal or inconclusive, an echocardiogram should be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically the first-line investigation for suspected absence seizures unless there are focal neurological signs or symptoms suggestive of a structural brain abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum electrolyte\u003C/strong\u003E abnormalities can cause various symptoms including altered mental status, but given the recurrent nature of these episodes and their typical presentation for absence seizures, it\u0027s not the most appropriate initial test.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["EEG is the most appropriate initial investigation for suspected absence seizures in children.","Cardiac causes should be considered in the differential diagnosis of transient loss of awareness in children."],"references":["Albuja AC, Khan GQ. Absence Seizure. In: StatPearls [Online]. 2022. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499867/","Kessler SK, McGinnis E. A Practical Guide to Treatment of Childhood Absence Epilepsy. Paediatr Drugs. 2019 Feb;21(1):15-24. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6394437/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33659"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12481"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33659","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33659"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-16T11:56:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-16T11:57:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4988"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48709"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"t